item.title: The Smallest Gallery In The World... and more
item.content:encoded:
A friend and I went to Savernack Street, the smallest gallery IN THE WORLD, on Friday. It's an unexceptional one-story building on 24th and Vermont, and the door doesn't unlock although the gallery is open 24/7. How does this work, you ask?

The exhibits are viewed through the peephole!

Behold, this month's entire exhibit:

There was a colorful community theater just next door. I bet its door actually unlocks.

Also seen in SF on Friday: Dolores Park! I'd lived for 13 months in the Bay Area before experiencing this beautiful hillside park with amazing scenery.

One of many lovely Painted Ladies:

But the best part of the day was a store called Paxton Gate. It's like a 19th-century British colonial den of iniquity-slash-garden, covered in taxidermied game and insects and gemstones and ferns and phrenology busts. I've never walked into a better store. Unfortunately, the only picture I took--of a coruscating gemstone display--doesn't come close to doing it justice (neither does its website, which has the totally wrong tone for the store). You'll just have to visit.
